{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:41:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.1,0.07,0.06,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84786"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2527"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69082"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2368"},{"type":"tags","id":"2921"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84786"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a workplace check-up prior to starting a new job. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His father has a history of subarachnoid haemorrhage and end-stage renal disease. He works as an office manager and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The remainder of his examination is unremarkable. An ultrasound reveals multiple bilateral renal cysts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely pattern of inheritance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitochondrial","Autosomal recessive","X-linked dominant","X-linked recessive","Autosomal dominant"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with incidentally discovered renal cysts and hypertension, with a paternal history suggesting complications of polycystic kidney disease. The inheritance pattern and clinical presentation are typical of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance is most likely given the adult onset, paternal history, and typical presentation with hypertension and multiple renal cysts. ADPKD is caused by mutations in PKD1 or PKD2 genes and typically manifests in adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive\u003C/strong\u003E polycystic kidney disease typically presents in infancy or early childhood with significant morbidity and mortality. The adult presentation in this case makes this pattern highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked dominant\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked recessive\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance patterns are unlikely as the disease was inherited from the father. Since males inherit their X chromosome from their mother, X-linked inheritance from father to son is not possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance is also unlikely as mitochondrial DNA is inherited exclusively from the mother, and this patient\u0027s condition was inherited from his father.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EADPKD has various manifestations including renal cysts, hypertension, intracranial aneurysms (explaining the father\u0027s subarachnoid haemorrhage), and progression to end-stage renal disease. Management focuses on blood pressure control and monitoring for complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease typically presents in adulthood with hypertension and multiple renal cysts.","Family history of subarachnoid haemorrhage suggests intracranial aneurysms, a known complication of Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD).","Paternal inheritance pattern strongly suggests autosomal dominant rather than X-linked or mitochondrial inheritance."],"references":["Bergmann C, Guay-Woodford LM, Harris PC, Horie S, Peters DJM, Torres VE. Polycystic kidney disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018;4(1):50-. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-018-0047-y"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69082"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69082"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-11T10:56:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-11T10:56:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2527"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84786"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro